magicbook.gtlitecore.api.utils.functions

接口 Functor<T,F extends Functor<?,?>>

  • 函数接口:
    这是一个函数接口, 因此可用作 lambda 表达式或方法引用的赋值目标。

    @FunctionalInterface
public interface Functor<T,F extends Functor<?,?>>
    Functor
    从以下版本开始:
    1.0.0
    作者:
    Magic_Sweepy

    The functional interface Function is f: T -> R, which T is type of the param input, and R is type of return value. For example, if we want to transform a String to Integer, then we can define below: 

    
         Function<String, Integer> function = Integer::parseInt;
    Then we should input a param "testString" in "domain" T, and then, the function Function<String, Integer> will map it to R, i.e. 
    
         Integer result = function.apply("testString");
    In this code, Integer is R, and String is T. Functor is a higher version of Function.

    Functor is a higher version of Function, T means the param type, such as: if T is Integer, then Functor<T, F> will consists of a integer value maybe; F is the type of Functor<T, F>, and another constraint is F must be the subtype of Functor<T, F>. The method map(Function) is not like Function.apply(Object), it will contain a function Function<T, R>, i.e. f: T -> R, and then map it to F, this method will transform value of Functor, return a new Functor which consists of the transformed value. For example, if we create a class which implements this class: 

             public class FunctorImpl implements Functor {
             private String value;

             public FunctorImpl(String value) {
                 this.value = value;
             }
